I agree with this article. Tuples nicely unified multiple return values and multiple parameters. FWIW Scala and Virgil both support the _  syntax for the placeholder in a partial application.<p><pre><code>    def add(x: int, y: int) -&gt; int { return x + y; }
    def add3 = add(_, 3);
</code></pre>
Or more simply, reusing some built-in functions:<p><pre><code>    def add3 = int.+(_, 3);</code></pre>

The article lists two arguments against Currying:<p><pre><code>  1) &quot;performance is a bit of a concern&quot;
  2) &quot;curried function types have a weird shape&quot;
</code></pre>
2 is followed by single example of how it doesn&#x27;t work the way the author would expect it to in Haskell.<p>It&#x27;s not a strong case in my opinion. Dismissed.
